<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870630-0108 </DOCNO><HL> Texas InstrumentsGets Military JobFor $556 Million</HL><DD> 06/30/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> TXN GQ BA NPH LK HPCAEROSPACE (ARO)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas Instruments Inc. won a $556 million contract to supply high-speed anti-radiation missiles, or HARMs, for U.S. and allied stockpiles.    Designed to home-in on radar signals, the HARM is the primary U.S. aerial weapon for knocking out hostile, surface-to-air missile launch sites.    Under the contract, Texas Instruments will deliver 1,410 missiles to the Air Force, 977 to the Navy and 188 to West Germany. The company also was awarded a $5.9 million Army contract to upgrade M-48 tanks for delivery to Turkey.    Boeing Military Airplane Co., a unit of Boeing Co., received a $43.4 million Air Force contract for B-52 aircraft equipment.    Magnavox Electronic Systems Co., a unit of North American Philips Corp., got a $24.2 million Navy contract for P-3 aircraft equipment.    Units of Grumman Corp. were issued contracts totaling $19.7 million for A-6E and F-14 aircraft production and E-2C aircraft improvements for the Navy, and electronic equipment for the Air Force.    Lockheed-Georgia Co., a unit of Lockheed Corp., received Air Force contracts totaling $18.4 million to repair C-141 aircraft and improve production plant facilities.    Hercules Inc. won a $15 million Army contract to operate a munitions plant at Radford, Va. </TEXT></DOC>